    <p>You'll learn to recognize fleeting pre-meltdown cues in high-functioning teens by understanding what these signals look like in real time and logging observations for collaboration with therapists and teachers. By catching these subtle signals early, you can intervene during the open window — reducing escalation and fostering calmer outcomes for the teen and their support team.</p>

    <div class="direct-answer">
      <strong>Quick answer:</strong> Subtle meltdown signs in high-functioning autistic teens occur during the build-up phase and include clenched jaw, eye contact changes, clipped tone, and repetitive looping questions. These signals flash for seconds to minutes — the only window where redirection is neurologically possible. Once a full meltdown begins, that window closes.
